******
[1] Cholera - Mozambique (Sofala Province)
Date: Mon 30 Mar 2015
Source: AllAfrica, AIM (Mozambique News Agency) report [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201503310109.html


The Mozambican Ministry of Health has confirmed that cholera has spread to the central province of Sofala with, to date, 260 cases, but no deaths. The figures for Sofala released at a Maputo press conference on Mon 29 Mar 2015 are that between 1 and 14 Mar 2015, there were 129 cases in the Sofala district of Caia, 91 in Nhamatanda, and 40 in the provincial capital, Beira.

Beira Municipal Council, however, flying in the face of the medical evidence, has denied there is any cholera in the city, claiming that the people hospitalised have only been suffering from severe diarrhea.

At a Beira press conference on Thu 26 Mar 2015, the Sofala provincial director of health, Chico Sande, reacted to the council, pointing out that the health authorities relied on laboratory analyses of samples of fluids taken from the patients. These proved the presence of the bacterium that causes cholera (which goes by the scientific name _Vibrio cholerae_). Exactly the same laboratory analyses had proved the presence of cholera in Caia and Nhamatanda.

--
